normalization.p:
This edition follows the manuscript spelling as far as possible. I write
michi on the basis of nichil, though it is never written out.
The manuscript explicitly writes sed in an expanded form rather than set. It records both
menbra and membra;
unquam and umquam;
the former of these variants are generally more common.

Examples of word division include
non nisi;
non nunquam;
nec non (with a few exceptions, especially in the added chapter 106);
non nulli;
nec dum;
ac si;
et si;
si quando. Although
in tantum appears as intantum in the manuscript, in and most other prepositions are usually joined to the following word in the manuscript, and I have silently divided these.
